// A generic function's body is type-checked abstractly (type variables become
// a permissive wildcard), so a *structural* body error is caught even when the
// function is never called — i.e. never monomorphized into a concrete instance
// codegen would otherwise check. Here `len` yields i64 but `bad` declares bool.
import { len } from builtins;

fn bad(v: any[]) -> bool { len(v) }

fn main() -> i64 { 0 }
--- errors ---
error: fn "bad": body returns i64, but the declared return type is bool
 --> ./tests/cases/generics/errors/err_generic_body_unreachable.aipl:7:28
  |
7 | fn bad(v: any[]) -> bool { len(v) }
  |                            ^^^^^
